{"title_page": "Cordelia Stanwood", "text_new": "{{short description|American ornithologist}}\n'''Cordelia J. Stanwood''' (1 August 1865 \u2013 20 November 1968) was an American [[ornithologist]] and wildlife [[Photography|photographer]]. One of her great achievements was the creation of [[Birdsacre Sanctuary]], also known as Stanwood Wildlife Sanctuary. Before being known as an ornithologist-photographer, Cordelia was a teacher and principal. She taught both grammar and art during her lifetime.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.birdsacre.com/cordie.html|title=Birdsacre - Stanwood Wildlife Sanctuary - Cordelia's Story|last=|first=|date=|website=www.birdsacre.com|publisher=|access-date=2016-11-13}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nCordelia was born to a wealthy merchant's daughter and a sea captain in [[Maine]]. When she was fourteen, Cordelia moved in with her aunt, also named Cordelia, and her family in [[Providence, Rhode Island]]. In 1886, Cordelia J. Stanwood graduated from [[Girls' High School of Providence]] and was successful there. For the next year, she trained to become a teacher at [[Providence Training School for Teachers]]. She graduated in 1887, and her first teaching job was at [[Messer Street Training School]]. Cordelia desired to become [[Critic Teacher]] at the school, so she studied in [[Martha's Vineyard]] for a summer. This was where she first met Henry Bailey, an artist who eventually became a teacher and friend. Five years after being hired as a teacher, Bailey persuaded Cordelia to attend the [[Normal Arts School]] in [[Boston|Boston, Massachusetts]]. Cordelia was also a principal at this time. While she graduated and did well at the school in Boston, she did not find employment. She then went back to Providence, Rhode Island, and taught. Until the year 1900, Cordelia taught in other places in [[Massachusetts]] and [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://maineanencyclopedia.com/stanwood-cornelia/|title=Stanwood, Cornelia|last=May-McGrath|first=Elizabeth|date=2008|website=maineanencyclopedia.com|publisher=This entry was posted in People (non-government), Society and tagged bird sanctuaries, birds, cornelia stanwood, Maine, nature preserves, ornithologists, S, wildlife refuges.|access-date=November 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Beginnings in ornithology==\n[[File:C Stanwood USGS migration card Flicker.png|thumb|Sighting of a Flicker, Reported by Cordelia J. Stanwood]]\nAt the age of 39,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.birdsacre.com/cordie.html|title=Birdsacre - Stanwood Wildlife Sanctuary - Cordelia's Story|website=www.birdsacre.com|access-date=2016-11-13}}</ref> Cordelia had a \"nervous breakdown\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=American Women Afield: Writings by Pioneering Women Naturalists|last=Bonta|first=Marcia|authorlink=Marcia Bonta|publisher=Texas A&M University Press|year=1995|isbn=978-0-89096-634-1|location=Texas|pages=114\u2013124|quote=|via=Google Books}}</ref> and stopped teaching. She moved back to [[Ellsworth, Maine]], where she spent the first fourteen years of her life. During her recovery, Cordelia started bird watching. She both wrote about the birds she observed and took pictures of them. Her findings and writings were shared in journals. While she grew up in a home of means, she did not have much funds to go around when she was older. Cordelia insisted on being independent and made money on her own. This often came from doing farm chores or selling the crafts she would make. Other income came from articles she wrote that were published in farming magazines.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Marcia Bonta]] says in her book, \"Too proud to accept help from anyone, even her siblings, she was reduced in her old age to selling greeting cards from door to door.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Photography==\n[[File:Alder Flycatcher (Empidonax alnorum) nest.png|thumb|184x184px|Picture of Alder Flycatcher by Cordelia J. Stanwood]]\nIn 1910, Cordelia published her first observational study titled, \"The Hermit Thrush: the Voice of the Northern Woods.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> Her career as a photographer started in 1916, and the [[American Ornithologists' Union|American Ornithologist's Union]] presented her portrait in the [[Library of Congress]] in 1934. She later gave the pictures she took to the [[Acadia National Park]] and her notes to the Ellsworth Bird Club.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Death and Birdsacre==\nCordelia J. Stanwood died at age ninety-three on November 20, 1968.<ref name=\":0\" /> Her final home and land became the [[Birdsacre Sanctuary]] and is considered a National Park. Cordelia's writings, photographs, and findings live on at Birdsacre Sanctuary as well as places such as the [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stanwood, Cordelia}}\n[[Category:1865 births]]\n[[Category:1968 deaths]]\n[[Category:American ornithologists]]\n[[Category:Women ornithologists]]\n[[Category:American women photographers]]\n[[Category:Photographers from Maine]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American ornithologist}}\n'''Cordelia J. Stanwood''' (1 August 1865 \u2013 20 November 1968) was an American [[ornithologist]]. She was also known for her wildlife [[photography]]. One of her great achievements was the creation of [[Birdsacre Sanctuary]]. Before being known as an ornithologist and wildlife photographer, Cordelia was a teacher and principal. She taught both grammar and art during her lifetime.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.birdsacre.com/cordie.html|title=Birdsacre - Stanwood Wildlife Sanctuary - Cordelia's Story|last=|first=|date=|website=www.birdsacre.com|publisher=|access-date=2016-11-13}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nCordelia was born to a wealthy merchant's daughter and a sea captain in [[Maine]]. When she was fourteen, Cordelia moved in with her aunt, also named Cordelia, and her family in [[Providence, Rhode Island]]. In 1886, Cordelia J. Stanwood graduated from [[Girls' High School of Providence]] and was successful there. For the next year, she trained to become a teacher at [[Providence Training School for Teachers]]. She graduated in 1887, and her first teaching job was at [[Messer Street Training School]]. Cordelia desired to become [[Critic Teacher]] at the school, so she studied in [[Martha's Vineyard]] for a summer. This was where she first met Henry Bailey, an artist who eventually became a teacher and friend. Five years after being hired as a teacher, Bailey persuaded Cordelia to attend the [[Normal Arts School]] in [[Boston|Boston, Massachusetts]]. Cordelia was also a principal at this time. While she graduated and did well at the school in Boston, she did not find employment. She then went back to Providence, Rhode Island, and taught. Until the year 1900, Cordelia taught in other places in [[Massachusetts]] and [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://maineanencyclopedia.com/stanwood-cornelia/|title=Stanwood, Cornelia|last=May-McGrath|first=Elizabeth|date=2008|website=maineanencyclopedia.com|publisher=This entry was posted in People (non-government), Society and tagged bird sanctuaries, birds, cornelia stanwood, Maine, nature preserves, ornithologists, S, wildlife refuges.|access-date=November 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Beginnings in ornithology==\n[[File:C Stanwood USGS migration card Flicker.png|thumb|Sighting of a Flicker, Reported by Cordelia J. Stanwood]]\nAt the age of 39,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.birdsacre.com/cordie.html|title=Birdsacre - Stanwood Wildlife Sanctuary - Cordelia's Story|website=www.birdsacre.com|access-date=2016-11-13}}</ref> Cordelia had a \"nervous breakdown\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=American Women Afield: Writings by Pioneering Women Naturalists|last=Bonta|first=Marcia|authorlink=Marcia Bonta|publisher=Texas A&M University Press|year=1995|isbn=978-0-89096-634-1|location=Texas|pages=114\u2013124|quote=|via=Google Books}}</ref> and stopped teaching. She moved back to [[Ellsworth, Maine]], where she spent the first fourteen years of her life. During her recovery, Cordelia started bird watching. She both wrote about the birds she observed and took pictures of them. Her findings and writings were shared in journals. While she grew up in a home of means, she did not have much funds to go around when she was older. Cordelia insisted on being independent and made money on her own. This often came from doing farm chores or selling the crafts she would make. Other income came from articles she wrote that were published in farming magazines.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Marcia Bonta]] says in her book, \"Too proud to accept help from anyone, even her siblings, she was reduced in her old age to selling greeting cards from door to door.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Photography==\n[[File:Alder Flycatcher (Empidonax alnorum) nest.png|thumb|184x184px|Picture of Alder Flycatcher by Cordelia J. Stanwood]]\nIn 1910, Cordelia published her first observational study titled, \"The Hermit Thrush: the Voice of the Northern Woods.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> Her career as a photographer started in 1916, and the [[American Ornithologists' Union|American Ornithologist's Union]] presented her portrait in the [[Library of Congress]] in 1934. She later gave the pictures she took to the [[Acadia National Park]] and her notes to the Ellsworth Bird Club.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Death and Birdsacre==\nCordelia J. Stanwood died at age ninety-three on November 20, 1968.<ref name=\":0\" /> Her final home and land became the [[Birdsacre Sanctuary]] and is considered a National Park. Cordelia's writings, photographs, and findings live on at Birdsacre Sanctuary as well as places such as the [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stanwood, Cordelia}}\n[[Category:1865 births]]\n[[Category:1968 deaths]]\n[[Category:American ornithologists]]\n[[Category:Women 